Â«This is one of those "miraculous" release album that have popped up in 
the late 80's and early 90's about a 70's lost album or "gem". This group
got its name from a famous line from a record label executive not being 
impressed at these guys's live demonstration and told them: "Get Your 
Gear And F##k Off".Â» 

Â«So these songs never got a release until 89, and come from 73 and the 
last two tracks from early 74 (all in mono), and they got released on the
anecdotical label Background whose catalogue is full of extremely 
obscure (but rarely interesting) releases. Not much is known about the 
band's members past and future musical careers outside of this release.Â»
